According to economists, a notice that the plan is being adopted should be the first significant psychological factor for a revival of financial markets.
However, there is a 'discouragement' afterwards, because of the complex mechanisms that could help the markets in practice.
The plan must be effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a market stabilization package should look like", Democratic Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
The Commission has not yet decided on the matter.
Representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to finalize the government fund.
The Commission has also taken the view that the Commission should be able to take a decision on the basis of the information provided by the Member States.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must be effective in the market.
The recovery plan still needs to be continued, but I think we are on track", Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also having a significant impact on the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are working to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
The idea is to reassure investors that Asian financial markets are in the first time zone where a congressional decision could affect business on Monday.
But it is not yet clear when both houses of the US Congress will vote on the bill, and it is unclear whether the negotiations could fail at the last minute on a problem.
The lawmakers hope it will be passed in the next few days.
But the law will undergo some changes.
The total amount of aid for the scheme is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
But Congress can block the distribution of the remaining money if it feels that the program is not doing its job, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in the negotiations
The President has veto power over this decision, but Congress can override his veto.
But despite these changes, the basic idea of the program has remained, which was based on obtaining financing to buy bad mortgage securities that have fallen in value because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to pay back their mortgages.
"We worked it all out.
The House should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, then the Senate on Monday", said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
President Bush also expressed satisfaction with the progress.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and "appreciates the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Restriction of golden parachutes
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said the legislators had agreed on responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing concessions and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies participating in the programme and to set up a committee to oversee the fund.
This is to be run by the Ministry of Finance.
"We've worked very hard on this and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important to the market and to all Americans", Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for homeowners who are having trouble repaying their mortgages.
