Whether the plan is adopted now or early next week is not decisive in Marek's view.
"Much more importantly, congressmen agree to support the plan and pass it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement to have a goodbye is the most important thing at this moment", Marek stressed.
Duel on knife edge: MP3 players against cell phones.
We will advise you on your choice
While almost every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
So, of course, it looks like it's better to just buy a phone.
Nevertheless, there are plenty of reasons to get a standalone player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the demands of the future owner.
I'm sure it's hard to buy a great, expensive record player at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc album.
Once such musical innovations do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
But if you have art rock, jazz or blues on your shelf, you probably dream of at least one of these.
So it's the same with music on the road, so with compressed music, in simple terms - MP3 music.
Again, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand kroner on a player, but a Pink Floyd fan will probably find it hard to afford a twenty-krone headphone from the market.
Two extremes, with enough room for each.
The selection is wide.
The life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can do much more than just play music, but what cell phones can do, they can't even do in a hint.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the basic functions of calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, it has a better camera, a worse one, and maybe it can navigate.
And if you add the smartphones and the communicators, you've got almost a little computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take pictures.
But the universality of mobile phones also has its drawbacks.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you'll need to recharge it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy-consumers.
Few phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, but most are much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more powerful.
So you should expect that cheap phones will not be able to play music for more than a few hours.
If you do have to use the phone occasionally, you might want to buy a charger for the office - even for more expensive devices - to be sure.
You won't have this problem with MP3 players, even the less good ones can last at least nine hours of uninterrupted operation on a single charge.
Another problem is when you want to play music on your phone.
Unfortunately, only a small number of devices have a USB port, and not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can play music directly on a storage medium, but few card readers can handle the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With players, you don't need any special software, except for the iPod.
You just need to feed the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most mobile phones and players set up their own music library, sorted by artist name, album title, genre, or user rating.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address book, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iRiver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a particular device, you should ask about the battery life, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound and, of course, the comfort of use.
If music is your main setting and you listen to it only briefly every day, for example on the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Which is something almost any phone can do.
You also don't have to control the music formats that a phone or a player can handle.
MP3s are what everyone is making, and most of the music you're going to get is going to be in that format right now.
The format is one of the most common, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also make it possible to buy music online.
You just have to go to the relevant websites of a provider (or another provider) via the mobile Internet and you can buy a song or an album.
This service in itself can be a powerful argument for why you should get a music phone.
Unfortunately, the providers' offer is poor and is mostly limited to quick radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
But it is generally expected that this type of music sales (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones.
If you feel like listening, reach for the phone in your jacket pocket while the player lies at home.
But it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless voice-over device.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only a few MP3 players.
For many, the greatest advantage of music phones will be in the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three or four thousand crowns you can get a decent walkman.
The biggest handicap for most of them is that they don't have regular headphones.
The best and most technically advanced phones with a 3.5 mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand kroner.
The advantage of the players is that they are easy to operate.
The simplest - and not necessarily the cheapest (see selection) - players can really be used by anyone.
A minimum of functionality, similarity in operation to the former normal cassette recorder or, for example, the record player is obvious.
There is no danger of collision in the form of a mistaken mobile internet connection and a subsequent horrendous data bill.
What device should you use now?
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable storage media (M2, microSD, etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns will be enough.
But be careful.
The basic models generally only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones can read 8-GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, go to Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton, or whatever.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you will not have to put more than 1100 kroner on the table.
If you're one of the more sophisticated listeners, you'd rather get specialized cell phones -- walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate MP3 control buttons, and the user experience is similar to that of a single MP3 player.
The farthest away is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series phones have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold individually.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours maximum) are provided by MP3 players of the aforementioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider will be in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I should .
The Czech mobile market is quite mature, with Czech providers offering virtually all services as well as those offered by their Western European partners.
However, something is missing - a virtual vendor that forces the traditional ones to lower prices.
Maybe this one won't keep you waiting.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight.
It may seem paradoxical, but there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and penetration is well over 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain about the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
This is often echoed by the Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no room in the Czech Republic for another provider.
It is likely that a traditional provider with its own network would not have many opportunities (and would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
The introduction of virtual providers into the mobile market was the main cause of a significant price reduction, to which the traditional mobile operators had to respond.
Before the entry of companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the UK market, there were similar votes as in the Czech Republic.
But it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February this year, we reported on the launch of the mobile-only service provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the company has managed to attract more than 100,000 customers, making it the fifth largest provider in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually present themselves as low-cost companies - offering cheap phone calls and SMS, but often with a less extensive service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
However, as Mobilking's example in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to target a non-clichéd target group.
This is a company that is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust", says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also take hold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone's spokesman Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment where most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services".
In the Czech Republic, the mobile operators say that there is no chance
But it's almost certain that when a virtual mobile phone company takes over the Czech Republic, it won't be Mobilking.
"While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very promising.
It will be more likely to be a market entry of Mobilking in other countries in our region", said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has long been a sign of the GTS Novera group, which wants to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate segment.
"We have a strong interest in offering not only fixed network but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them,' said Pavel Kaidl, the group's press spokesman.
Maybe better times are coming.
The first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year, according to unofficial information.
But so far, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
'At this moment we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a full-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area", says Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefónica O2 in his statement to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also pointed out by other suppliers.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds, in rare agreement with O2's statement: 'We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build.'
And she adds: "T-Mobile's network will have hardly any virtual vendors by the end of the year.
We would have to have a concrete offer at this point to be able to think so short-term".
Vodafone is focusing more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the best from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile internet.'
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the suppliers
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor be given easier access to the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something is also evidence of the long back and forth that led to the emergence of U:fon.
The most powerful pressure on ČTÚ came from T-Mobile at the time of the launch of U:fon.
This is also shown by the publicly available information on the ČTÚ websites.
But U:fon is a good argument for not allowing a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, in particular, on its services.'
However, in view of this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
The Czech Republic, unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries, is unfortunately not competent to intervene in economic competition.
The Commission has the exclusive competence of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
But this was his very typical attitude to the whole problem.
'The entry of a mobile virtual network operator into the market would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile network operator and a virtual network operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional providers", said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in his reply to our inquiry.
Such a wording would not surprise the representatives of the suppliers.
This is more than a matter of concern from an authority which represents the interests of consumers and which is supposed, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses his position on the market.
In particular, as Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers operate quite normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephone services".
However, it is likely that pressure on the proper functioning of the market and price reduction are not in the ÚOHS's interests.
What is really shocking in this case is the almost touching consistency of the three mobile operators in their responses.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolute unchanging price of petrol at petrol stations is surely just a coincidence and the result of a fierce competition.
'The Authority has not found in this case any evidence of anti-competitive conduct and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the suppliers has a dominant position on the market and therefore does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its actions on the market.
The telecommunications regulator is also likely to lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile market to virtual providers", Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the entry of a virtual provider into the market.
And the mobile phone company has, logically, the monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily has a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if this argument is not accepted, it should be at least a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not succeed in extending the competence of the ČTÚ to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
I can do it if nobody's watching
The first thing that is not taken into account is the operation of some pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but these are only partially public.
The Commission has also taken the view that the Commission should be able to take a decision on the basis of the information provided by the Member States.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only a select few.
The funny thing is that the company is acting as a traditional corporate customer to the operator, ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a key customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resales.
"If there are cases you describe, it could be a breach of the contractual terms, which we will deal with, which could lead to the termination of the cooperation with the company concerned", Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this problem.
It is, however, unlikely that such a thing is not being talked about by the operators of mobile telephone services.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers may be involved.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
The fact is that these companies generate significant profits from their activities and, unlike the actual virtual suppliers, are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the potential problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but the services of these companies are used by only a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as normal customers of mobile operators".
But that alone would seem strange to the CTU.
Furthermore, a further question arises for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to this, why block off a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities and if it does not wish to, it does not have to be satisfied with the providers' declaration that they did not know about it and that their terms of business would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been emphasised several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers into the market has led to a significant fall in the prices of the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, traditional providers have tried to prevent them from emerging in a more or less practical way.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the advanced countries, however, it was at this time that the regulators intervened, not in the interests of the mobile operators but in the interests of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator, and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole thing away like a hot potato.
In our experience, we cannot escape the impression that in these cases, uncertainty in competence is more than favourable.
But let's not throw the gun in the face.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be back in motion.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) further applicants.
And the Czechs will finally stop paying more than the rest of Europe for their phone calls.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Where is my homeland?" at a celebration of the Czech Statehood Day.
The anthem was re-recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo singing, in choral form and in an instrumental version.
The vocal composition was taken over by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The editing of the hymn versions is done by Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions at once.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national anthem is one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had already told the Czech Radio that he had selected singers with young, representative voices, who are distinctive and popular for the solo versions.
"From the beginning, I tried to keep the diction clear, both with the choir and with the orchestra, so that the text could be understood and harmony could be created", says the conductor.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the Stendtheater in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was composed by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people adopted it spontaneously.
The first stanza of the song then became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
