Prague transport operators will also be using a chip for the first time on Wednesday.
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will go down in Prague transport history as the date when the first passengers to board a subway, tram or bus carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The Commission has also proposed a number of measures to improve the quality of the information provided by the Member States.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it simultaneously redeemed on their chip card at the information centres and branches of the transport operators at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
The coupons are also available on the Internet since yesterday on the websites of transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon.
Those who use the Internet can really forget the subway ticketing window, where they have regularly had to wait in long lines for their paper tickets.
The coupon is purchased online and is then played on the Opencard at one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"These places also offer a desk with trained staff who can advise on internet purchases and also play the coupon on the map", says Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on the Opencard at self-service machines, which are located in some subway lobbies.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket counters, which passengers may have already noticed at the subway stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are five of them in the city at the moment, but by the end of the year there will be eighty", adds Opatrný.
The coupon is controlled by an automaton instead of the driver
Operating the vending machines, which will be operational tomorrow, is simple.
You just need to enter the chip card, and the pre-purchased coupon will play itself out.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
The suburban trains and bus lines 300 to 499 are used to reach the capital, mainly by residents of the municipalities in the Central Bohemian region.
"On the trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport system, train attendants have readers that allow them to check the validity of the coupons by time and zone", explains Filip Drápal of the ticket control organisation Ropid, which compiles the timetables for Prague's transport operators.
Suburban buses have card readers at the driver's counter.
The chip card must not only be shown to the driver when boarding, but the Opencard must be placed in a marked place on the side of the cash register.
This is used by the driver to check the validity of the coupons displayed.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the displayed coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information", Drápal says.
A passenger who does not travel on suburban buses and does not know when the coupon expires can go back to the self-service ATMs where the coupons are displayed on the card.
This will display the information on the validity of his documents on the device's display.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States
The Sudeten Germans had requested the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States in 1945.
This is according to a letter in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would at least like to live under the auspices of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans reportedly asked the U.S. president to do so.
This is shown, among other things, by a letter preserved in a private archive and now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau ask the American President not to allow the return of the "debt swap" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure that the American units are not entering German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", says a letter signed "People who care about the fate of the Sudeten".
