If the US president doubts the sentiments of the Bohemian Germans, it is sufficient that he initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest to decide whether the inhabitants want to become part of the US or live under the protection of the US.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of postwar history, some contemporary witnesses believe that it paints a good picture of the Sudeten German expectations of the time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans had to at least suspect that their deportation from the Republic would be negotiated, few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Still others thought they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who is from Budweis, also confirms this.
He was a Budweiser German in the Baltic Sea during the war.
