Even rats have feelings
A rat or a sparrow fleeing danger, does that mean it feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have feelings too.
But how can we know if they feel the same way when they behave like us?
The online journal "Edge" has been publishing contributions by famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a series of selected answers to the question "What do you believe to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else has been able to prove so far, whereas we can't even prove that other humans have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But once we turn to another species and we tackle issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter rough terrain because the hardware doesn't match.
When a rat is in danger, it does what many other animals do: It pretends to be dead, flies, or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, which some scientists conclude is a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to translate our subjective experience to that of animals.
For one thing , the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and execution / control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
So at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there's reason to believe that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature may lie in the linguistic nature of man: Since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, you could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly be influenced by it, so that animal consciousness, whatever its form, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
That's why it's hard to tell what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If it is something internal and subjective, which cannot be measured or analyzed because of the special hardware, based on our own experience, then its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my presentations relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more accessible scientifically.
You could study the consciousness processes of animals without regard to their content, and that's exactly what happens in studies of the short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, relies more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: they may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the process of visualization.
What about the sensations?
I'm guiding them back to the fact that an emotional system like fear is activated in a conscious brain that is aware of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies working memory.
Sensation is closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates, and humans in particular.
In connection with the linguistic nature, there are subtle degrees of feeling, because with the help of words and grammar we can differentiate and categorize states, to attribute them to others besides ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body sensation regions of the cortex and the brainstem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, but focusing more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in sensations across species.
I cannot dispute this in theory, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what seems to be fear in rats and humans is likely to feel the same in both cases: But how can we check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A fox flee when threatened, does he feel fear?
In my view, mere similarity of behaviour cannot prove similarity of experience.
Neural comparisons help us to see that rats and humans have similar brain stem sets, whereas cockroaches don't even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove it in humans, how would you prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have senses.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I'd rather study emotional behavior than rat emotional sensations.
But there's progress at the neural level, if you measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as I don't study language and consciousness in rats, I don't study sensations, and I don't know if they exist.
You may think I'm shortsighted, but I'd rather be ahead than running into a wall all the time.
I'm just a practical emotional guy.
