Debate on bilingual education: education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior fellow in California Studies and senior director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is co-author of Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice.
Addressing the Hispanic electorate is a complicated task.
Barack Obama's proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama's campaign notes that "black and Hispanic students are less likely to graduate than white students", which is true.
To close this achievement gap, Obama's education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition phase in education for those who are just learning English.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the achievement gap.
Take Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in East Los Angeles, for example.
The majority of the students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom are newcomers, are learning English.
Yet, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-graders passed the state test in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of fourth-graders scored well on the English test.
This amazing success has been achieved by different methods than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School emphasizes checking and practice, constant checking of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate exceptions.
Moreover, the school is taking the approach of an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should be paying attention to, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasises the almost exclusive use of the English language in technical education.
Mrs. Mikels, who is opposed to the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had had a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico, and 12 months later you would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize him.
"It works", she noted, "it works for us".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with a large share of Hispanic and other English-speaking students?
The school's performance would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within his own party (the national education associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama's answer uncertain.
While he agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about "English only" legislation.
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your child can speak Spanish".
If Obama really wants to close the achievement gap, he should carefully consider models of education that work, instead of dismissing and trivializing them.
