Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia has once again shown why he is considered by some to be the best long-distance runner of all time, after breaking his own record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday, becoming the first person to complete the 42.2-kilometer distance in under 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With the victory on the flat course in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous result of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he had achieved last year in Berlin.
Gebrselassie, 35, has thus set his 26th world record in his versatile career, in which he has achieved at least one world championship title or set a world record on every mile from one kilometre to the marathon.
Last month, dyslexia caused him to miss the Beijing Olympic marathon, perhaps overly concerned that air pollution might worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he signed up for the competition in Berlin.
In almost ideal conditions - in sunny conditions and 9 degrees at the start and 13 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won at an average speed of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
Since the switch of long-distance runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat from Kenya, the record time for marathon has fallen by more than 2 minutes in the last 10 years, since Ronaldo da Costa from Brazil won in Berlin in 1998 with a 2:06:05.
After his victory on Sunday, Gebrselassie told the press that he had had cramps in his thigh two weeks ago and could not train for a week.
Apparently, he's refreshed after the break and not rusty.
"I'm so happy", he told reporters.
"Everything went perfectly.
I started training again a week ago and had some doubts today, but everything was great".
He has been criticized - particularly in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for over-orchestrating his races, generally avoiding many of the world's top marathon stars, relying too much on the race leaders as if it were a track race, and setting world records over the course of the competition.
But this criticism hardly harms the size of Bruges as a long-distance runner.
Accompanied by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie had reached the midpoint of the race in 1:02:04.
Two elite runners from Kenya, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, continued to challenge dyslexia after the pace makers gave up.
Just over three miles from the finish, Gebrselassie made his final run to part ways with Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his best time by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In women, Irina Mikitenko, originally from Kazakhstan and now German, has completed a remarkable year by setting the seventh-fastest time ever with 2:19:19.
The world record of 2:15:25 is held by Paul Radcliff of Great Britain.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko had surprisingly won the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games due to problems described as a back injury, but recovered to win in Berlin and improve her best time in her third marathon by five minutes.
She has planned her run well, having a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners start first, but overtake after 30 kilometres.
Askale Tafa Magarsa from Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31, while Helena Kiprop from Kenya came in third in 2:25:01.
The pride and hardship of the black population in a city of a very special kind.
Hidden among the lush lushness of Orlando's surrounding amusement parks, a few miles from the glittering, noisy, and gigantic bustle of the city, lies a quiet city where the pride and intricacies of African-American culture are on display.
Eatonville, the first all-black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, 3 croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison".
It's a pilgrimage site now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee are here for the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to honor the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city she describes  and which made her a tourist destination by including her in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression  is and remains in many ways a place of a very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, as poised, and as private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing".
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate on race relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told", says Hortense Jones, 59, a native of the city and a member of the city's oldest church.
It has to be true".
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It's both a historic example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is both a literary stronghold and an example of the sometimes condemned, sometimes praised, black culture of the rural South, rooted in American slavery.
It is not surprising that the inhabitants of this place are both proud and cautious.
And so the concern about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as Hurston is known.
She introduced the world to her hometown in books written from the heart and in oral language, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Travel Guide transformed the city, which is located right off of Route 77, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida, into the setting of black history and human drama.
As brazen as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston Lear led the store to Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"On the left of the street", she wrote, "is the brown-and-white-painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds, always tended by Howard Miller, who can hardly read or write".
She also mentioned the new husband of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and what-ever fits in with classrooms".
In just a few hundred words, Hurston thus linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriages, and sex.
This was definitely not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were", said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added: "Some people didn't like it".
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came into town in a state of rage, she did so mostly without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today is somewhat fanciful of her venerable style of dress.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, but many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora", said Mr. Franklin.
"But she never stayed too long", he added as he rocked his chair on a back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary of Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
There was no big memorial service in Eatonville, no big public readings.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy in the least", says Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a 2003 biography of Hurston.
The turning point came in the '80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to build a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main street of the community.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950's, the fight against racial segregation brought hatred to the community.
"At this time, a bunch of white boys would come and throw oranges and stuff at the people sitting out", Mr. Franklin said.
"There was even a woman who was killed in the process.
They threw a watermelon out of the car".
In 1955, Hurston, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, questioned the Supreme Court's demand to force integration by describing its decision in Brown v. Board of Education as "offensive rather than respectful of my race".
Residents today say that while the desegregation was positive in some ways, it weakened the group unity in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black kids used to be hugged - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged your teacher in the evening", says N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Protecting the Eatonville Community.
This could be maintained, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't embrace your white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide", said Ms. Nathiri.
But civil rights helped make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons -- black writers, actors, and artists who overcame prejudice, as she did, with positive self-esteem and statements like, "How can anyone deny themselves the joy of my company!
I don't understand it".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out to Hurston's unmarked grave and began her fight to revive her fame.
Five years later, a much-lauded biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway was on the bookshelves, making it once again part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community started planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the county could do with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the county turned its back on its road construction plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway have brought the city to life, accelerated the process at top speed, and brought real civic pride", said Ms Nathiri.
Mrs Boyd put it a little simpler: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the long-distance road project has contributed to a change in the city's self-image.
More and more tourists came, including Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending church here since 1993, and locals began to appreciate the past.
Eatonville was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a distinctive Florida town, just six miles from downtown Orlando, and it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It's 90% black these days.)
Outsiders looking for the history and significance of Eatonville are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, prior permission is required, and certain items - such as the mural in Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in the field - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a penchant for dark red, are still afraid that their sheltered community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew, an increased degree of homeland pride was also born.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, no worse, no better, and as proud, creative and industrious, silly and mixed up as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in city government or the police, who he says might need some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this town is nothing compared to all the others,'" said Alondra Kenon one Sunday after church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city".
Here in New York, we speak financial Latin fluently.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspaper stands and the giant TV screens in Times Square, they would not even realize that they were in the middle of a debacle.
You would never believe that above their heads, in shoe-shaped offices with glass facades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York City are having the worst day of horror every day since the stock market crash of 1929.
Suppliers still push metal tea bags along sidewalks with loud bangs and carry muffins-laden tablets for breakfast.
Latinos still creep between apartments like human pack animals loaded with about 50 folded T-shirts hanging from a yoke-like pole lying on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting at sidewalk food stalls for their breakfast bagels, and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn't feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon, when I decided, because of all the doomsday talk, to open a new savings account.
Although I had decided to put my due date on the quiet late afternoon at my JP Morgan Chase headquarters, there were already about 20 people in line.
Not the cash register for cash withdrawals or deposits, but the customer service counter where regular customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy's department stores, and new customers open accounts.
Most of the people before me, I later learned from Starr, my "personal bank employee with a license", were in line for the same reason I was.
But unlike me, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks, in places they commuted from, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrift (a bit like a construction savings bank), co-operative banks and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state and say they treat their customers like family.
In the last year, 15 of these banks have quietly gone bankrupt.
Over the past few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went into administration bankruptcy, and as New Yorkers drove home over the weekend last Friday, Wachovia, another bank with $440 billion in savings, was looking for a bailout buyer.
Fearing another collapse, the office and store workers who waited in line before me took their cash to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank that is responsible for most of the bailout purchases on Wall Street.
Normal New Yorkers have been getting their hands on a lot of liquid financial Latin in the last few weeks.
A woman who was on the phone in my Chinese supermarket was referring to Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank and its skinny-looking CEO, Dick Fuld, with as much familiarity as if she were gossiping about a lazy coworker.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment block, has moved on from our usual conversation topics about Brad and Angelina and my grocery delivery.
"I have all my savings in money market funds now", she told me after I visited the bank.
"I've changed, I'm not taking any more risks".
Muslim graves desecrated during a right-wing slide in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a leftist from the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party of Austria, and Filip Dewinter, a member of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party, take part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, 17 January 2008, representing the organization Cities Against Islamization.
They carry traffic sign-style signs depicting a mosque, crossed by a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same weekend as far-right parties recorded significant gains in the country's parliamentary elections.
On the night of Friday morning, more than 90 graves were severely damaged at the cemetery in Traun near Linz in what police say was an organized operation.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols such as the David Star on some of the graves, but law enforcement officials believe this was an attempt to cover up the motives of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It's not clear if the incident is in any way connected to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the grave desecration, which took place as the Muslim religious month of Ramadan drew to a close.
At the same time, a round of conscientious objection is being held in Austria after the country's right-wing swing in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The FPÖ and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that won almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law and some of their slogans were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the FPÖ, which won 18% of the vote, advocated a ban on headscarves and burkas and even expressed his dislike of foods generally associated with Islam.
At his last rally in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets on the grounds that these are political symbols of a continuous Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses conducted immediately after the election, which show that the far right is the most politically powerful bloc in the country, suggest that this new development is based on young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
