Gary Glitter, the glam rock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain.
Judges imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities controlling him that he was going to travel to Spain via France.
Kent police were granted a travel ban last Thursday after they presented evidence of Glitter's criminal history in child sexual abuse cases.
Glitter, whose real name is Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford County Court in Kent, but was represented by the law firm Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the Court reported: 'On Thursday 25 September, Kent Police applied to Ashford County Court for permission to prevent Mr Paul Glad from travelling abroad to France and Spain until 25 March.
Paul Gadd was not present in person".
As required by the sex offender registry, Glitter, 64, had informed the authorities that he intended to travel abroad.
He must inform the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He must also notify the police seven days before his planned departure.
Failure to notify the authorities could result in a prison sentence of up to five years.
Kent police said they would not discuss individual cases or Glitter's possible whereabouts in the country.
A spokeswoman for Kent Police said: "Kent Police will do whatever is necessary to protect children in this country and abroad".
"We think it's easier to control someone who's in the UK because we have a comprehensive system to effectively prevent any potential risks".
"It is the Kent Police's primary concern to protect the citizens of Kent and we are working closely together to monitor the behaviour of registered sex offenders in the country to minimise any risk to the public.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for molesting two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, Glitter flew to Bangkok, where he was scheduled to take a flight to London.
