The Thai authorities did not let him through passport control and he flew back and forth to Hong Kong.
He was also denied entry by the Chinese authorities and flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and border officials insisted he return to the UK.
Finally, he arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 on 22 August and stayed there while his lawyer David Corker went to Uxbridge Crown Court in West London, as Scotland Yard had successfully applied for permission to require him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter had previously been jailed for four months in the UK in 1999 for possession of child abuse images.
According to the Interior Ministry, Interior Secretary Jacqui Smith was reassured and pleased that Glitter had been prevented from traveling to France and Spain.
