In his project `Flamenco-people', German photographer Günter Bauer presents a varied theatrical presentation of some stage productions with singers, dancers and guitarists, a side of which he was little known to the artists.
With this proposal, the photographer creates a special iconography of the flamenco production on different levels.
The exhibition, which is part of the programme of the month of flamenco photography, ` reflects the international importance of flamenco, which is growing day by day', explains the artist, making it clear that `Flamenco-people' ` can be anyone, but when you look at the photos, the viewer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
The very ordinary people in the portraits are artists who are able to convey passion, sadness, joy on stage and thus move the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, you don't have to take pictures on stage.
Their personality and character is in their hearts.
What I was interested in was creating a personal atmosphere that would allow me to capture with my camera the characters of the greatest flamenco masters.'
In 1997, Bauer, inspired by the `Cante de las Minas' festival, set out on a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a digital camera.
Thanks to the camera's image sorting function and the material available, images were created that resemble classic photography.
The use of various stylistic means destroys the classical basis of the image, giving it the modernity and the idea of the farmer's understanding of flamenco: `Music with traditional roots, which changes and surprises every day'.
It is not just the dance, the singing or the playing of the instrument itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, which seduces the audience with his art.
The search for the essential, for a certain something that becomes visible in the form of hearing, of being, is and has been the definite aim of this work, which will be presented in the near future in the gallery of El Fotómata.
Famous flamenco figures including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo and others are among the narrow selection of the nearly seventy artists who were photographed.
The project became an anthology of flamenco and will soon be published as a book, with all the portraits from the exhibition.
