Drivers who may relapse because of the alcohol level will have to install the `Alcolock'.
The authorities order the driver, who has three official alcohol-related penalties, to install this system in his car, which prohibits him from starting the car while drunk.
The initiative was announced last June and is already part of the report of the Prosecutor General's Office, which says that it is a pilot project which will last for one year.
The purpose is to re-socialize the driver, who will then be given a course on the re-education of traffic behaviour.
In addition to the Prosecutor General's Office, experience has shown that the Ministry of Transport and the Technical Institute for Automotive Safety Foundation will also be involved.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of drivers who have been booked more than once for drunk driving are driving again.
The 'alcohol lock' would prevent this because it is a system linked to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver has taken an alcohol test; or if a higher than permitted alcohol concentration is detected.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the cost being borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of violations within the first year of their introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate their implementation, a legal reform can be achieved by the usual means, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is called for, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is not yet available in any Spanish market, although it has been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
