Some children talk at night
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the kids who talk in their sleep.
When it happens to you for the first time, at best you'll be scared, but in reality it doesn't matter.
This is a positive sleep disorder called sleep talking.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
Surely, more than one of you has been told that you spoke at night.
This phenomenon may occur occasionally (once in life, for example, during a high fever), or regularly (every day, once a week, once a month), and the next day the child may not remember anything.
There is no single cause for this phenomenon.
Often, people look for connections with other sleeping phenomena, such as nightmares, panic attacks at night, bedwetting, talking in their sleep, but there is no reason to do so.
As we mentioned earlier, it can be caused by high levels of fiber, stress, or overload.
In any case, it's a little-studied phenomenon.
The frequency of occurrence is highly variable.
It may be quietly speaking in single words, whispering, or it may be the opposite (screaming, crying, long discussions).
In cases where the expression is very intense, it is recommended that the child be observed and consulted by a specialist to see if there is a problem that causes fear and thus occurs.
We said it's a positive disorder, so it's not being treated, whether it's associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, sleep apnea or stress).
What you can do is take a series of simple precautions:
Try not to arouse the child before bedtime.
So, choose quiet play for the child and avoid stressful TV shows that are awful and a little too wild.
For nervous children who are recommended to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them to gain a measure of inner peace.
It'll help the baby sleep.
If you ever have a conversation in your sleep, try to stay calm.
Remember, it's harmless to the child, and the next day, he won't be able to remember anything that happened.
Helpful Advice
Don't wake it up.
It's useless, because the child is unconscious, so you'll pull him out of his sleep.
Although the child speaks, it sleeps, so it rests.
Remember, if the child is frightened after a few apparitions, it is recommended that you seek counseling or find out what the reason for the child's fear is.
If they understand what is said (which is not so common), the child is not pressured into doing an interrogation and getting more information.
You will not be able to do anything with it, because when the child sleeps, he is unconscious and cannot think about it.
