A Conversation - From the Blood That Became Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, for Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And most important, it has regained the public's trust, which had been badly shaken by the blood-tainted scandal of the 1980's and 1990's.
It is well known that during the 1980's the national blood supply, administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Donation Service, was contaminated with the HIV and hepatitis C viruses.
In the face of this tragedy and public discontent, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry in February 1994, headed by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances leading up to such a tragedy and to develop policies to prevent a repeat of this type of disaster.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces then set up a committee to develop a new system for managing blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
` In 1998, when Hema-Quebec began its work, only 38% of the people had confidence in Quebec's blood storage system, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through work in this area over the following years, we have regained the public's trust,' she says, before proudly pointing out that by early 2008 almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr Décary is aware that 'trust is a very fragile thing'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has been operating on the principle of prudence.
At the same time, we saw the emergence of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new form of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
And we had no idea that this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we refer to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which is to apply exclusion measures when you do not know it and when a disease is only progressing slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself in brain degeneration, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999 no blood was accepted from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proved beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the precautionary principle that we have applied makes perfect sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs), which allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor's blood, rather than the presence of antibodies to the virus as was the case with previous tests.
The NSTs have shortened the incubation period between the time the person is infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
So the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and not be detected, has been significantly reduced.
These improvements have made it possible to reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through blood transfusion to a considerable extent.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
` In other words, it would take 12 million cans of blood to get someone infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood cans each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood can occur.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable getting or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore your health,' says the CEO of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next 10 years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogens might get into your system.
Only last year, the Chikungunya virus was discovered on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects through the blood.
We must monitor continuously,' continues Dr Décary, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate care in addition to safe care.
` Demand is increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population is also affecting the blood donor network, which on average comprises only 3% of Quebec's eligible population.
Any healthy person 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On the average, 14% of those who donate their blood are rejected because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is common are excluded from donating blood for a year.
` With this 3% we can obtain an inventory which meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages of supplies are very rare.
But you have to replenish the members of this donor network when they get older and can't donate blood anymore.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but more importantly, to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that it is rare to find time to spend an hour donating blood,' laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only canned blood but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is used almost exclusively in severe burn injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
Once considered biomedical waste, cord blood contains stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
`We celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample a few weeks ago, and we plan to take more than 1,000 a year.
'We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,' explains Dr Décary, who describes this umbilical cord blood collection programme as very popular.
`Many mothers are convinced that they do not have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly programme in all hospitals in Quebec.
