Free speech - the Orwellian speech by Barrick Gold
In its 17 September issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, deputy managing director of Barrick Gold, a Canadian gold mine.
This confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company sought a defamation suit of six million against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening a 'public, transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge on the truth, especially not in cases of defamation, but on the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to speak one of their opposing opinions.
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defence and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mines.
The tactic in these unequal battles is often to ruin the defendants in order to force a compromise that silences the other side and also discourages anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to the public.
In contrast to what is commonplace in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada debates are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas rather than by sticking to sticks.
So it would have been enough if the goldmine had released its books and files and opened up a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent review teams that could have shed light on this question.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to have any faith in public opinion and is wiping out the petitions and letters in support of the writers of Noir Canada with a wave of the hand.
Mr Garver, could you explain how he can ask for a public debate and at the same time ignore the opinions of the public?
It seems that in the Vice President's world, that word only includes the well-paid lawyers, not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public supporting the writers and editors of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because they reject the brutal attitude of the goldmine.
This public is willing to listen and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag suit (in the course of the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just issued a request to the authors of Noir Canada, asking them to stop using this term...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, the Barrick Gold lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom to pursue academic research and the pursuit of truth, which are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to research and discuss topics that do not appeal to the rich corporations of the world, who else can?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the writers of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the academic world as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to limit this type of unjustified lawsuits.
