What was produced in the invoice factory of Zürich &amp; Co.?
On October 8, the trial of János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The defendants are charged with involvement in organised crime, gross negligence in damaging and defrauding businesses, and other criminal offences, including forgery of documents.
According to the prosecution, the funds obtained from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often covered by false invoices.
State funds and grants from the local government - a total of HUF 65 million - were partly paid into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation and partly into the coffers of private individuals.
The investigating authorities stated that fictitious invoices were presented for the tender money and that the clubs had not fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were forged.
The bills were bought at the market in Józsefváros, and the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue the invoices was made on that round trip north of Lake Platten, to which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
During this "exploration tour", Lados was to locate guesthouses and restaurants.
He requested invoices for consumption in order to be able to issue later invoices for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour and the Budapest Municipality based on these models.
These bills are said to have been manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who, according to our information, was responsible for the preparation of the relevant reports.
One of the goals of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer hall.
According to two invoices issued by Zuplag and Co in 2003, the catering establishment was supposed to have hosted the 90-person group of Biztos Pont Egyesület.
But now the head of the company says that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant all at once.
Another invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also showed serious errors of form and content.
A boarding house in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at a time, is said to have had 130 guests, according to the bill.
The imagination of the counterfeiters was also apparently unlimited in the case of Pigal Kft., a catering company whose accounting records do not even show up for the clients Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá, according to the prosecution.
According to the manager Győző Farkas of hvg.hu, he immediately realized that the documents were forged when he was presented with documents by the prosecutor's office during an interrogation.
"Our company name and tax number were misplaced on the stamp".
Furthermore, apart from formal errors, it was also incorrect to say that the establishment accommodated 100 persons when it has eleven rooms in total, which cannot accommodate so many persons.
The bill also stated that the restaurant had been closed for some time.
The prolific counterfeiters also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they targeted only offered travel abroad, and so they listed Hungary travel on the cash-only invoice, which was also contrary to the company's accounting practices.
As the investigation revealed, they also included VAT on the invoices, although travel agency services to a country outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The amount of VAT was incorrect on four invoices issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the establishment charges only 15 per cent VAT instead of 25 per cent, and the employees issue only machine invoices, but the documents are handwritten.
Another mistake made by the "accountants" was that in one case they had indicated "transport of goods" as a service provided, although this is not offered by the firm specialising in investment advice, the prosecutor's office said.
Further formal errors - incorrect invoice format, incorrect stamps - were responsible for the fact that the invoices issued by Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont were exposed as counterfeits.
The same is true of Ravenna Bt. and Kunfehértó sports warehouse, whose managers claimed that they never issued the invoices.
Another "mistake" was made by the forgers at HIB Kft. in Nyíregyháza: this company was in the process of being dissolved at the time (2001) when the group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület was said to have eaten there - the mass manager therefore stated that he did not issue the invoices himself.
Intentionally Forged
The other group of accountants are people who were fully aware that they would have to make fictitious bills.
At the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, the Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation has issued invoices for the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation, amounting to approximately HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the managing director of Collab Ltd. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft., which is also in liquidation, is also alleged to have cooperated with Zusslag and Co. In 2003, the GmbH allegedly supplied the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület with false invoices totalling HUF 5 million for non-performing services.
However, there was also little payment traffic, as the invoices were cancelled immediately after they were issued, which the persons concerned forgot to mention in their documents.
The third group of accountants comprises persons directly connected with the defendants.
One of them is Ivan Kubatov, the mailman of the Ukrainian manager of Delta Trió Kft., a Budapest-based but untraceable fuel and vehicle trading company.
It is alleged that this company issued several invoices for the sale of computer components, totalling approximately HUF 18 million, between October and December 2005.
According to the investigating authority, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005, acted as the buyer of these invoices.
The manager of this company was a Romanian, to whom the company documents were also to be delivered by Ivan Kubatov, between 2002 and 2005.
According to our information, during the investigation, Kubatov admitted to issuing invoices on behalf of GmbH to the Atlasz and Hoppá associations and to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and to having collected the equivalent of the invoices himself.
The companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were allegedly founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
In reality, however, none of these firms were active, which according to the defendant was due to a lack of orders.
Nevertheless, he was able to benefit from the companies: at the request of his partner, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who was in charge of preparing the company's constitution documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations linked to the contract, such as Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
In total, Kubatov is alleged to have issued 15 invoices totalling HUF 14,2 million to the organisations on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade.
The prosecution believes that Kubatov may have collected 10% of the invoice amount and VAT.
Kubatov is even alleged to have misused the company Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices - in this case the invoices were attached to Biztos Pont's applications.
The company Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted their applications to the non-profit organisation of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány ('TMA'), in January 2006.
Both received 500 000 forints each, but misused these amounts.
To cover this up, they submitted to TMA five fictitious invoices from Works Team Kft.
These bills were, incidentally, secured during a search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
The proceedings are now expected to be followed by a confession by some of the defendants to the proceedings of the forgery of accounts, as they had already been made before the prosecution.
It could be a sensation if the main accused, János Zuschlag, decides to make a full confession.
His previous statements have been less detailed, and although he has already promised several times to report on everything, his confession is still pending.
The question therefore remains whether this is in its interest, whether the Socialists have concluded a pact with it for the compensation of the bulk of the HUF 50 million of damage caused and whether Zuflag is willing to assume responsibility in return.
It is possible, however, that Zuschlag is now playing the "offended" role after his pleas for mitigation of detention and house arrest were met with deaf ears.
While other criminals who have caused far greater damage by committing economic crimes and have not compensated for it are free, or at least under house arrest, the Supplement is denied this possibility.
The psychology of oversupply - or why we're willing to pay more
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the items offered.
Neurologists and economists at New York University have now succeeded in discovering the neuroeconomic basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people do not want to be outdone in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even exorbitant prices.
Researchers have tried to explore the neurological pattern of this "game" by experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was asked to play a lottery, while the other was asked to participate in a gambling activity - in both cases, the active regions of the subjects' brains were examined by means of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex located below the cortex, was observed in losers of the auction, where outbid is a key factor.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also conducted research on the tracking of money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was told the true value of the product, and then they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged as winners of the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which would have been lost in the event of a losing game.
So the only difference between the two groups was that one group was focused on winning, while the other group was focused on losing.
But as proof of the hypothesis put forward by neurologists, members of the "against-losing" group were willing to bet higher than those in the "win" and "control" groups.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
The Commission has also been able to provide a number of proposals for the future of the European Union, in particular to the Council and the Commission.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved by the imaging neurological processes, so that we now have a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, professor at the New York University School of Economics.
Hepatitis: When should you see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated, which is because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - hepatitis and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases are different.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, they can be transmitted through the digestive tract (e.g., contaminated food or water); in hepatitis B, C, and D, they can be transmitted through blood and other bodily fluids (e.g., semen, vaginal discharge, or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against the A and B viruses, but there is no vaccine against the C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain, and diarrhea.
After that, the skin and eyes become yellowish, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and recovery may take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about one million people die each year from the more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people is on medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know they are sick, since the pathogen is subtly destroying liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention, such as regular controls, is essential.
There are three groups in which this condition is more common: those who received a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooers.
Currently, the number of people worldwide with chronic hepatitis C is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is advisable to consult a family doctor at the first sign of unknown origin.
If caught in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby reducing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
The 30th September is World Hepatitis Day, first celebrated in 2004 by patient organisations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, its origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
Recent research shows that religious faith acts as a kind of "painkiller" that has already facilitated the deaths of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment to see how belief in God affects the way people feel pain, reports Britain's Telegraph.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 religious and atheist individuals were each electrocuted while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
The results showed that the believers were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Using brain-scanning technology, it was even shown that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The study was the first in a research project involving scientists as well as philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
In the experiment, the subjects were attached to their left hand a sparkling device that gave the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: one, a 17th-century picture of the Mother of God by Sassoferrato, and Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with Hermeline".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose Vinci's painting because it was hardly different from the other painting and was felt to be soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time they received a total of 20 electroshocks in four stages, while they were either looking at the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported feeling "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if "concerned", and feeling "peace and quiet".
When viewing the religious painting, they reported about 12% less pain than when they were looking at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that you could produce similar effects with other powerful images even in atheists, just by finding the right photo.
"We would have to find an image that evokes very positive feelings, like a mother or a father", says the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practice of faith should change our personality, and in many cases it does", Wright said.
After these excellent results, the question remains, what effect would a Madonna painting by Leonardo or another similar painter have on the pain regulation of the faithful?
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary produce even better results?
You are what you say you are
On its tenth birthday, Google can rightly claim that it is in people's pockets as well as above their heads: it knows where people have spent their holidays, which doctors they go to, and what moves them.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the CEOs at Google.
And he's telling skeptics who are plagued by Orwellian horror visions that they're just missing the essence of Web 2.0.
In a recent interview with the Financial Times, Schmidt said that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, thus moving closer to the company's original goal of "ordering all the information in the world".
Schmidt explained that after ten years of changing the world, Google was still in the early stages of gathering information.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google could answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "Which job is really right for me?" but that software programs were not yet able to do so because they did not know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches, the search terms are recorded, as are the IP addresses from which the searches were made and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save their own search history and to use it later, so that the results can be generated much more accurately later, and the same logic is used for the so-called "Recommendations" which recommend tailored products and services based on previous preferences.
But users are wondering what happens in case of data abuse - "If you look at what I do" - some are worried about Google's data monopoly.
But in most cases, it is the potential power represented by the company that is the fear-inspiring factor, and not the guilt or fear of punishment, the desire for freedom, or the rebellion against power that many Internet users find repulsive.
However, it is a well-established fact that the search terms are not only stored but also, if necessary, passed on to third parties, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent crackdown on pedophilia in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information gathered from the community site called "Orkut" and also allowed the identification of pedophiles.
However, privacy-conscious users were still breathing in May when Google and civil rights group EFF successfully sued the FBI: so no provision in the Constitution can force Google to release information to the FBI on secret request in the future.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the release of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms in reference to the Youth Protection Act passed years ago, but has been deprived of the list of individual users, or their web and search terms list retroactively for two months.)
Google's image remains controversial: those who are reluctant to release their personal data for fear of losing their privacy by using Google services are lashing out at the company with the indignation due to companies that present themselves as conservative.
However, the American "geek culture" which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users sees in them the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs", in contrast to Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require user identification codes and provides its services free of charge, so that an open, constantly updated source code and software package seems far more attractive, youthful and cool than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, geeks are blindingly ignoring the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet - a relationship that has come to the forefront in recent years, especially thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
The Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, that is, users intentionally leave traces and use the available channels of communication, and even if the scale varies individually, the main thing remains the same, which is to show themselves publicly.
The average teenager can manage their profile on multiple community portals at once - from Facebook to Xanga, connect it with other services like Twitter, or music services like last.fm, and finally integrate it into a tracking system like FriendFeed or Blip.fm. They can also run blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries posted on Flickr or Picasa.
And a series of other examples prove it: looking at the party photos from the night before, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful boyfriend was having fun with, or the employee gets fired for overly honestly expressing anger about the company's management on his blog - one thing is for sure: The term "privacy" has been completely reinterpreted.
Whoever lives online is what he gives away - that is the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who tries to keep something secret, or even to circumvent Google's monopoly, is happy to do so -- like with Scroogle, a tool that, while it accesses Google's search engine, intentionally leaves no trace.
Many people do not register on community sites intentionally so that they cannot be found, but Google's online applications, such as word processing and graphics tools and RSS feeds, can also be circumvented by alternative versions that are not tied to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible user profile.
Meanwhile, the public is waiting impatiently for Google to reveal its true face.
At its current value of $156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising space is threatening the revenues of advertising agencies, and the ever-faster introduction of services is preparing to break the heads of not only Microsoft but also other software developers.
Critics, however, also find the opposite worrying: for example, the company's management completely rejected a protest by employees after the company's own kindergarten fees were doubled, and the management also thought that the multiple meals for employees were too expensive.
The company's internal policy is that no new service is advertised in advance, but only when it is already available.However, events in the coming months and years could have a major impact: while some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning or archiving project is now reaching a stage where the company will soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, others are rather concerned about the "Health" system, which allows the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database is already providing the material for the next generation of science fiction writers -- like "Scroogled", Cory Doctorow's famous novel, which describes in the best Orwellian way a future in which a human being becomes terribly approachable thanks to data obtained from Google.
