Smart cars mimic the flight of the bumblebee
What better way to develop new technologies for accident prevention than to imitate the obstacle sensors found in nature?
The bees, for example.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented, where Nissan engineers were inspired by Hummel to create new accident prevention systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C car-robot-controlled biomimetic system, a mini car with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of helping to develop a system that avoids all collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The bee's compound eye, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To mimic the function of the compound eye, the researchers took up the idea of laser-controlled distance measurement.
This detects obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 metres, calculates their distances and sends signals to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the robot car immediately changes course, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tires at the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this is purely instinctive.
"If it were not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles", explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, since this technology is the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The whole process has to reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that has to happen in a split second.
However, unlike bees, the evasion cannot be up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the rotation of the tires.
While the bees here have an infinite number of ways to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotation of the robot car, or acceleration and deceleration.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries which are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It doesn't have to store them, or to produce an intuitive, logical response based on previous maneuvers, so it only uses a handful of KB of memory at a time.
It doesn't need gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology which Nissan estimates will be in series production within the next ten years.
Another application could be GPS satellite navigation, which deliberately guides the driver around obstacles and leads him to his destination.
