According to the Central Statistical Office, domestic sales prices rose by 0.1% in August 2008 compared to the previous month and by 12.9% compared to August 2007.
Export prices were 1.1% higher than in July 2008 and fell by 3.9% compared with the previous year.
Due to price changes in the domestic and export sectors, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in 2007.
Domestic sales prices increased only slightly, i.e. by 0.1%, compared with the previous month.
The sales prices of manufacturing also rose only slightly - 0.1% - since July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was for leather goods (2.8%) - primarily for bags and belts - where the increase was 4.6%, and for shoes prices rose by 2.5%.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials drove prices for chemicals and manufacturing considerably higher (1.6%).
Price declines were recorded in crude oil processing (1.4%), electrical and technical equipment (0.9%) and slightly in wood processing (0.1%).
Prices in papermaking, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In other branches of manufacturing, price increases were recorded between 0.2 and 0.9%.
In the main domestic markets of industry, such as electricity, gas, steam and water, prices rose by 0.3% in August, mainly as a result of the increase in gas prices introduced on 1 July.
If we look at the domestic sales markets of the manufacturing industry in comparison with the previous year, the prices in the crude oil processing sector have risen the most (32.4%).
The metalworking sector saw an increase of 13.2%, while the increase in the manufacture of food, beverages and tobacco was 11%.
Price declines were observed in the textile industry (2.5%) and in electrical and technical equipment (0.3%).
The rate of increase in prices in the other manufacturing industries was between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry rose by 10.2% last year.
Prices of electricity, gas, steam and water rose by 18.7 percent year-on-year.
On the domestic market, the highest price increase was recorded in August in the capital goods sector (0.7%).
In the manufacturing sectors, prices for consumer goods rose by 0.3%, while in the energy and processing sectors they remained unchanged compared with the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was observed in the energy and reuse sector (16.8%) compared to the same period in 2007.
In the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, prices rose by 6.8%, while in the capital goods sector prices fell by 1.4%.
The export prices of industry, measured in forints, rose by 1.1% in August compared with the previous month, but fell by 3.9% year-on-year.
The domestic currency weakened by 1.7% against the euro and by 7.1% against the dollar, and compared with August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5% against the euro and by 15.9% against the dollar.
