We can greatly limit this damage by taking steps such as reducing the volume and the duration of noise exposure.
In its report, the European Scientific Committee points out that if users of portable music devices listen to loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, then the legal limits on maximum noise levels at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who cross this music threshold risk losing their hearing completely within five years.
This represents 5-10% of the users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
Roma, Alemanno gives the go-ahead for the Commission for the Future of the Capital
We start today, finish in March, get the balance in June.
The Commission has been meeting this morning in the new headquarters behind the Caracalla thermal baths.
In six months' time, President Marzano and the other 49 Members of the Commission will draw up guidelines for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the city and the municipal council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present the strategic plan for Rome in June with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and Mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and represents all political, social and cultural opinions", emphasises Alemanno. "It will propose a development plan for Rome, the political responsibility for which will remain with the city and the local council.
There is no redistribution of responsibilities, only the desire to have a place where one can develop a major project for Rome.
In March, their work will be finished and the Commission will be dissolved again, as such a project must have a definite end date.
In June, the mayor announced, we will present the strategic plan in which we will use the work done by the Commission".
To those who question the Commission's competence because its opinion is not binding, Alemanno replies: 'Everything depends on the work the Commission will do and on the quality of its proposals.
If they produce quality results, as the Attali Commission did in France, and this will certainly be the case in Rome, their contribution will be fundamental.
Too often politics is concerned with the everyday problems and emergencies that arise from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to look at a longer period of time to be able to work seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city with a deeper perspective".
The Mayor of Rome is keen to make clear that 'this Commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free, it will not cost the citizens of Rome a cent and it will make us think.
According to Alemanno, "it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetic nor static, in order to allow our city to make a leap in quality - which it really needs - and thus take a common step into the future".
A future, according to the Mayor of Rome, which "will not be confined to the current municipal boundaries but will look much further", not only in terms of Rome's role as the metropolis and political capital of Italy, but also as the future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean".
