The elite are in danger
This phenomenon was already apparent a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the White House's $700 billion austerity package: a large portion of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by the New York Times' report yesterday, which reports how the ongoing crisis is dividing the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and the business community, and those neoconservatives who are hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, and is winning voters, especially in the South and the center of the states.
This section of the party owes its rise mainly to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
This example is only a small part of the great changes that the present economic earthquake is heralding or even already representing: not only in the United States, but throughout the West and perhaps beyond.
The crisis in both the States and in Europe seems to be accelerating the long-feared events which are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the extraordinary renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is in fact a decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and manage a vast amount of the wealth of private households living in a single country.
This is a direct political problem for governments: how to deal with the families concerned, who are also a huge constituency.
The crisis is thus economically global, while politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have become marginalised and to have lost its right to speak: the EU, divided into different national and international conflicts, is the clearest proof of this.
So now everyone is counting on the intervention of their own state, rescue plans, new rules, and most importantly, the distribution of aid funds: since the crisis has become more and more serious, only the United States is in the economic position to save itself without outside help.
And besides the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: two conditions which cannot be overestimated  under certain circumstances , which no international organization or market would otherwise be able to use in a similar way.
The new emphasis on the national-state element is also in perfect harmony with the growing importance recently attached to a closely related sector in the economy: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is now, when we have long been convinced that we have entered a connected whole, a realm of ever-differentiating technologies, of the intangible, that we must suddenly realize how our future will increasingly depend on the essentially material things: water, crops and oil.
While all of these can be transported from one place to another in the world, they are nevertheless linked to a narrowly defined piece of land  a territory.
Thus, one who has such territory has an advantage over another who lives in an area that is barren, waterless, or free of oil.
I now come to the second novelty, which requires a brief introduction.
If you say territory, if you say government, if you say politics, you say leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to be producing two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respectable leadership, so the need for someone who knows how to run things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation at the existing leadership, especially the economic one, which has proved to be inadequate and full of shadows.
Finally, there is a deeper and in a sense even more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, a sense of futility, a sense of distance, all of which are directed at a whole class of managers in Western countries.
It seems that the conviction is thus opening up among large sections of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite but their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is increasingly alien and obsolete to the majority.
The demand for leadership is thus underground fuelling a branched but powerful movement of disempowerment of the ruling class and the traditional political establishment, manifested in unforeseen "riots" by voters and in the indirect shift in the collective mood of recent times: from the rise of the Conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, to the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of the American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here too).
It seems that the old elite, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their magazines, their intellectual creditors, some would say their format, have more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value in relation to what is happening today in the lower social strata of the West, and is being further amplified by the financial crisis and pushed to the over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would be an exaggeration to speak of a "revolt of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The Super Glue That Can Blow Up Walls
To overcome the forces of gravity with a glue and to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which now seems to be almost at the finish line.
Using a glue applied to an area of only 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers were able to fix a 100-kilogram body on a vertical wall.
STUDIO  is an American journal that has published the results of researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material the research team has developed is an improvement on the adhesive materials already used, which use a special carbon structure called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged on a stack of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists were inspired by the geckos' feet, which are covered with microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect grip.
Tests with various materials, such as glass teflon and sandpaper, showed that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the reptile's feet and "can be easily removed from the wall", says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a perishable glue", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe, but researchers are thinking about a less fascinating use, like connecting electrical devices, because nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in the field of space.
So for now, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH  The University of California, Berkeley, is also working on a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, scientists in California present a glue made of microfibers that, like a hair, cleans itself of dust by moving on a surface, thus maintaining a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed especially in summer because of their refreshing quality and their richness in vitamins, can cause serious health damage when taken together with certain vital medicines, since they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, has repeatedly pointed out the risks of packaged and fresh fruit juices in connection with medication. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm: One glass of apple, orange, or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption of certain vital medicines to the point where they are virtually eliminated, thus endangering the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice has already been suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some medicines, such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular medicines, anxiolytics and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
MEDICINS IN CONTACT  In a report two years ago, the same drug agency warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mixture, stressing that they should be careful about what they drink when taking drugs such as diazepan or methadone.
It's NOT JUST GRAPEFRUIT  According to experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
This is why Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano, appeals: 'Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still uncertainties, do not hesitate to ask a pharmacist or doctor", emphasizes the expert of the ANSA agency.
