Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package is released
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software is gaining more and more users, both at home and in the office, among freelancers and in public administration, as a free substitute for Microsoft Office.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers, overseen by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with some novelties: in addition to a revised and now more Spartan design of the Start menu, it has finally achieved a guaranteed compatibility from the ground up with Apple's Mac OS x operating system, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version.
The Commission also opposed compatibility with Microsoft Office 2007, which allows OpenOffice to read new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting are also some new features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier to send via email, for example. This includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules while preserving the original appearance of the page.
This also allows the creation of "hybrid" PDF files, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format to include the elements of a spreadsheet and a word processing system.
Collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by several users, thus avoiding conflicts when changes are made; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a query to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are currently releasing various OpenOffice features on the cloud, with the final results to be published in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. It follows the English version, which has been available on Mirrors since Friday.
Apart from Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
The installation CD can be sent to your home or office upon request.
While the free offer can be an incentive for the spread of the software in private households, it is also in the business sector where OpenOffice could be the big winner: after all, several public administration institutions and schools have already switched to OpenOffice.
In fact, it does not even lack a training programme, which means optimal support for small and medium-sized enterprises and thus even business opportunities.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word-compatible word processing program; Calc, the spreadsheet program aimed at displacing Excel; Impress, for creating PowerPoint-like presentations; Dbase for running databases instead of the more familiar Access; and, lastly, Draw, a graphics module.
The target for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads  a target which can easily be exceeded with 3 million 600 thousand downloads already achieved.
