Goodbye to the old cinema paradise  cities are closing their historic cinemas
The historic cinemas are closing because of the multiplex cinema.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes".
This picture by Giuseppe Tornatore is a powerful description of what is happening in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of large multi-screen complexes in the periphery, means in the long run the death of the one-screen cinema in the centre, a process which not only seems inevitable and irrevocable but also has the characteristics of a cultural crime.
The film, which won him the Oscar and the Grand Prix de Cannes 20 years ago, tells the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia of living in a world of cinema that is lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, are clear: in the last five years, the vast number of 316 traditional cinemas has been forced to close, the majority of which have been in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely in these three regions that the greatest number of these modern cinemas have been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the list, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec. "Although it is useful to have new structures, the main priority is to preserve the existing one, because when a venue closes in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to go to a multi-screen cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
The remaining budget for the trade union fund is extremely low: the state's debt burden is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from an ethical and moral standpoint that the government does not respect the existing laws.
The sector would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year to survive".
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city to decide, out of concern for the old cinemas, to protect them by means of an agreement between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, aimed at protecting and supporting traditional cinemas, both in the historic centre and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax advantages for the cinema operators and public transport benefits: driving to the restricted areas of the centre and parking at cheaper rates.
"It is a welcome initiative", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow our example and also come up with new concepts.
But of course we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to counter the superpower of the multiplex, because after all, today's audiences are more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the decisive point that led me to found the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been toying with the idea for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to one side so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
