When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the big ones are running up
It is a never-ending source of money, covering over 70% of the planet's surface, and only now do the world's major energy companies seem to be realizing this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; it is no coincidence that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil fell in the 1980s, the idea of marine energy was lost on the minds of many, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of global energy demand could be met by the energy generated by ocean waves.
This would be twice as much energy as is currently produced by nuclear power plants.
Added to this would be the tides and currents.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in the north of Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are now turning to marine energy production.
"Chevron is looking into these technologies", said a spokesman for a company familiar with the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering whether to work with us".
The Commission has not yet decided on the proposal for a regulation on the use of the term 'common market' in the United States.
This is a sign not to be underestimated, especially when one considers that in Alaska, the United States continues to drill for oil and that President Bush has only recently started plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; although details are not known, observers are reporting an increasing interest.
Technology that needs improvement.
Experts say that the technology is still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects like the one in Portugal and also in Scotland are of a rather small scale and do not seem to be causing any serious environmental problems.
However, large-scale energy production requires technologies with a much greater impact on the environment.
There are several ways: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves that move the buoys up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure inside the swimmer by means of pistons and cylinders.
This one powers a turbine, which in turn powers a generator.
The power is sent to the coast via underwater pipelines.
